{
  format: 1
  name: uuid-uppercase-input-canonicalization-unspecified
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["§A.1", "§D.2"]
  tags: ["uuid", "identity", "unicode"]
  note: '''Attack surface, but genuinely unspecified. An attacker supplies the same UUID
once lowercase and once UPPERCASE, hoping to either (a) mint a second identity for the
same UUID, or (b) alias onto the victim row. Annex A.1 fixes the canonical *wire* value
of a uuid as the 'lowercase hyphenated JSON string', and Annex D.2 fixes the canonical
*key text* as the 'lowercase hyphenated form'. Both describe the canonical output form;
NEITHER states an input-acceptance rule for a non-canonical (uppercase) uuid literal
supplied as a key. Three behaviors are each defensible under the text:
  - normalize to lowercase, so the second insert collides on the same key (rejected);
  - reject the uppercase literal as a non-canonical uuid (invalid at admission);
  - accept it verbatim as a distinct key (contradicting D.2's single canonical text, but
    not forbidden by any input rule).
The spec does not pin which, so the second insert's outcome is unspecified. Recorded as a
spec gap: Annex A/D define canonical uuid form without a normalization-or-reject rule for
non-canonical inputs.'''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.uuidcase@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      keys: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "uuid"
        marker: "text"
      }
      $public: {
        keys: {
          $mut: {
            add: ".keys + { id: @id, marker: @marker }"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { call: "public.keys.add",
      args: { id: "0191c1a0-0000-7000-8000-000000000000", marker: "lower" },
      expect: { outcome: ok } }
    // same UUID, uppercased hex digits: acceptance/normalization is not pinned
    { call: "public.keys.add",
      args: { id: "0191C1A0-0000-7000-8000-000000000000", marker: "upper" },
      expect: { outcome: unspecified } }
  ]
}
